[lm/research/modal-runtime] Resolve Modal runtime controls (complete)
Collect current first-party behavior and pricing for candidate GPUs, Volumes, web serving, concurrency, autoscaling, deployment, and shutdown.
Known 2026-07-17: Modal lists gpu=RTX-PRO-6000; NVIDIA specifies 96 GB GDDR7; Modal listed $0.000842/s. Values must be refreshed when the cell is admitted.
Known 2026-07-19 (GPU multi-count gap): Modal's GPU guide sentence enumerating multi-GPU counts ("B300, B200, H200, H100, A100, L4, T4, L40S support up to 8 GPUs... A10 supports up to 4 GPUs") does NOT name RTX-PRO-6000 at all, in both the live page and local mirror. NVIDIA's own RTX PRO 6000 Blackwell Server Edition product page (specs table) also states no multi-GPU-per-node or NVLink/NVSwitch figure -- only single-GPU specs (96 GB GDDR7, 512-bit bus, 1597 GB/s bandwidth) plus Multi-Instance GPU (MIG, up to 4 isolated instances WITHIN one GPU, not multi-GPU scaling). No source documents a multi-GPU count for RTX-PRO-6000 as of 2026-07-19; must be confirmed via a Modal trial or Modal support.
Known 2026-07-19 (autoscaling/shutdown, Functions): scaledown_window default 60s idle timeout before shutdown; startup_timeout default 30s before a non-ready container is terminated as failed; configurable per @app.function/@app.cls via max_containers, min_containers, buffer_containers, scaledown_window; dynamic runtime overrides via Function.update_autoscaler() (reset on next deploy).
Known 2026-07-19 (Servers primitive, @app.server(), distinct from Functions/web_server): target_concurrency drives autoscaling (soft limit only); scaleup_window/scaledown_window tune responsiveness; startup_timeout applies to port-listening readiness; periodic health checks -- too many consecutive failures terminates+replaces the container; on scale-down, inflight requests get up to exit_grace_period seconds, then SIGTERM, then 30s grace, then SIGKILL; requires Modal-Key/Modal-Secret proxy-auth headers unless unauthenticated=True is set; routing_region (us-east default, us-west, eu-west, ap-south) plus optional compute_region (cost multiplier); Modal-Session-ID header enables sticky sessions; zero warm containers returns 503 immediately (no request queueing, unlike Functions); Servers lack built-in retries and configurable timeouts -- client/app layer must implement.
Known 2026-07-19 (deployment lifecycle): a rollover appears as a new version in deployment history and can use rolling or recreate strategy; rollbacks are available.
Known 2026-07-19 (Volumes): distributed, write-once-read-many-optimized filesystem; up to 2.5 GB/s bandwidth (not guaranteed); billed via daily snapshot of total storage, deleted data may still bill up to 4 days; mount options read_only and sub_path apply per-container-mount (not stored on the Volume); modal.Volume.from_name + vol.commit() needed to persist writes.
Known 2026-07-19 (Secrets): key names <=16,384 chars, values <=32,768 chars per key-value pair; injected via secrets=[...] on @app.function/@app.cls; multiple Secrets merge in list order, later entries override earlier on key clash; creatable via dashboard, CLI, or Secret.from_dict() in code.
Known 2026-07-19 (Web Function proxy auth, distinct from Server auth): requires_proxy_auth=True on fastapi_endpoint/asgi_app/wsgi_app/web_server gates public access behind Modal-Key/Modal-Secret headers; under RBAC, tokens can be scoped to specific Environments.
Known 2026-07-18 (Endpoints primitive, aka "Modal Inference endpoints"): a managed LLM-serving primitive distinct from Functions/web_server and from raw Server, created via `modal endpoint create --model <hf-repo-id>` (modal.com/docs/guide/endpoints, modal.com/docs/cli/latest/endpoint). Built on top of the Server primitive (dashboard's "Source" panel shows Server-based generated code). Catalog families: Qwen, Kimi, Gemma4, DeepSeek, Nemotron, GPT-OSS, GLM; also accepts custom weights from a private HF repo (--custom-hf-repo/--custom-hf-revision/--custom-hf-token) or a Modal Volume (--custom-volume-name/--custom-volume-path, directory must contain config.json), always against a catalog base model for recipe selection. Serves ONLY the OpenAI Chat Completions API under /v1 (GET /v1/models to list) -- no /v1/responses or /v1/messages route is documented in the guide or the CLI reference. Auth: proxy tokens (Modal-Key/Modal-Secret headers) by default, --unauthenticated opts out, RBAC workspaces need `modal workspace proxy-tokens allow`. Placement: --routing-region (us-west default/us-east/eu-west/ap-south) and --colocate-compute (pin compute to routing region, incurs region multiplier). Lifecycle: `modal endpoint list`, `modal endpoint stop` (tears down containers, stops billing). Pricing: standard compute rates, scale-to-zero by default, no idle cost, autoscaling overrides adjustable in UI. Data retention (modal.com/docs/guide/security): Modal Inference endpoints are zero data retention -- request/response payloads are never written to disk, pass through only as in-flight network traffic, TLS terminates at Modal's edge proxy and tunnels directly to the container; Modal's own retention table lists Server and Auto Endpoints payloads as "Not stored -- proxied directly to your container", versus Functions' 7-day TTL on inputs/outputs.
Report: dated handles and numeric inputs needed by runtime design; no preferred policy verdict.
-> ssm
