[lm/research/engines] Resolve admissible serving engines (started)
Build a first-party support matrix for the exact Qwen3-Next architecture and artifact candidates across vLLM, SGLang, TensorRT-LLM, and any challenger that passes all gates.
Known 2026-07-17: vLLM's Qwen3-Next recipe uses TP4, prefix caching, and Hermes tool parsing; Qwen's official SGLang command also uses TP4. Neither is a selection or proof that one 96 GB GPU cannot work.
Known 2026-07-19: TensorRT-LLM's PyTorch-backend "Model-Feature Support Matrix (Key Models)" lists Qwen3NextForCausalLM as a supported row, but this pass did not capture the table's column headers, so the row's Yes/No/Untested values cannot yet be mapped to named features -- gap remains. A footnote on that table flags relatively low accuracy for Qwen3-Next-80B-A3B on the SciCode-AA-v2 benchmark specifically. TensorRT-LLM's separate hardware support-matrix page (reference/support-matrix.html) lists only GPU architecture families (GB200 NVL72, Blackwell, Grace Hopper Superchip, Hopper, Ada Lovelace, Ampere) -- no per-SKU "RTX Pro 6000 SE" entry was found. A prior web-search claim that TensorRT-LLM's docs "explicitly list the RTX Pro 6000 SE" in a hardware matrix is NOT corroborated by direct fetch of that page and should be treated as unconfirmed pending further check.
Known 2026-07-19 (vLLM tool calling): --enable-auto-tool-choice plus --tool-call-parser selects a model-specific parser; vLLM's own docs recommend --tool-call-parser hermes for Qwen2.5/QwQ models (chat template already ships Hermes-style tool-use support), and a separate qwen3_xml parser exists specifically for Qwen3-Coder models. No Qwen3-Next-specific parser is named in vLLM's tool-calling doc; Hermes is the documented fallback for the Qwen family generally, but this has NOT been independently confirmed for Qwen3-Next-80B-A3B -- gap remains. Streaming tool-call extraction is a first-class parser interface (extract_tool_calls_streaming). tool_choice modes: auto (schema-constrained only when strict:true is set on a tool, gated by VLLM_ENFORCE_STRICT_TOOL_CALLING default true) / required (always schema-constrained) / none.
Known 2026-07-19 (VS Code API-type coverage): vLLM's OpenAI-compatible server exposes /v1/chat/completions (matches VS Code's "Chat Completions" apiType), /v1/responses (matches "Responses"), and /v1/messages (matches "Messages", Anthropic-compatible) -- all three VS Code Custom Endpoint API types have a corresponding vLLM server endpoint.
Gates: load support, selected quantization/GPU support, VS Code-compatible API, streamed automatic tool calls, tool-result continuation, and measurable runtime statistics.
Report exclusions with evidence; do not carry unsupported engines into the bakeoff.
-> ssm
